<b>He was an advisor, he managed huge</b>

238
01:08:41,966 --> 01:08:44,733
<b>building projects and later wrote the</b>

239
01:08:44,733 --> 01:08:46,366
<b>seminal biography of Charlemagne.</b>

240
01:08:47,199 --> 01:08:49,333
<b>His entire career was built on his</b>

241
01:08:49,333 --> 01:08:51,100
<b>written intellectual abilities.</b>

242
01:08:51,566 --> 01:08:54,333
<b>And then there's Tuchodah, the wife of</b>

243
01:08:54,333 --> 01:08:56,366
<b>aristocrat Bernard of Septimania.</b>

244
01:08:57,133 --> 01:08:59,666
<b>She wrote a detailed handbook for her son</b>

245
01:08:59,666 --> 01:09:02,199
<b>William, filled with advice drawn from</b>

246
01:09:02,199 --> 01:09:02,933
<b>Christian Latin</b>

247
01:09:02,933 --> 01:09:05,666
<b>literature from patristic sources.</b>

248
01:09:06,233 --> 01:09:08,633
<b>The complexity and the sheer range of</b>

249
01:09:08,633 --> 01:09:11,633
<b>literature she synthesizes, it strongly</b>

250
01:09:11,633 --> 01:09:13,266
<b>suggests she was fully</b>

251
01:09:13,266 --> 01:09:15,733
<b>educated, probably at Aachen itself.</b>

252
01:09:16,066 --> 01:09:18,600
<b>Which proves high-level Latin literacy</b>

253
01:09:18,600 --> 01:09:21,133
<b>existed among the Carolinian aristocratic</b>

254
01:09:21,133 --> 01:09:24,033
<b>laity for both men and women.</b>

255
01:09:24,566 --> 01:09:26,800
<b>After Charlemagne dies, the intellectual</b>

256
01:09:26,800 --> 01:09:28,233
<b>systems he created</b>

257
01:09:28,233 --> 01:09:30,766
<b>didn't vanish. They diffused.</b>

258
01:09:31,133 --> 01:09:33,533
<b>Monasteries like St. Gall provided what</b>

259
01:09:33,533 --> 01:09:35,333
<b>the sources call an</b>

260
01:09:35,333 --> 01:09:37,233
<b>"etenerent notarial service".</b>

261
01:09:37,800 --> 01:09:39,966
<b>Scribes didn't just stay writing prayer</b>

262
01:09:39,966 --> 01:09:42,066
<b>books, they traveled out into surrounding</b>

263
01:09:42,066 --> 01:09:44,000
<b>communities to provide professional</b>

264
01:09:44,000 --> 01:09:46,333
<b>written documentation services to</b>

265
01:09:46,333 --> 01:09:47,633
<b>non-monastic people.</b>

266
01:09:48,500 --> 01:09:51,966
<b>Charters for gifts, sales, exchanges of</b>

267
01:09:51,966 --> 01:09:55,066
<b>property, high-stakes transactions that</b>

268
01:09:55,066 --> 01:09:56,933
<b>cemented who owned what land.</b>

269
01:09:57,366 --> 01:09:59,266
<b>And the procedure shows how important the</b>

270
01:09:59,266 --> 01:10:00,433
<b>document had become.</b>

271
01:10:01,066 --> 01:10:02,933
<b>Witnesses in these transactions had to</b>

272
01:10:02,933 --> 01:10:04,433
<b>confirm they saw the</b>

273
01:10:04,433 --> 01:10:05,500
<b>document being written.</b>

274
01:10:05,733 --> 01:10:06,966
<b>Their hands were physically</b>

275
01:10:06,966 --> 01:10:08,800
<b>placed on the completed document.</b>

276
01:10:09,166 --> 01:10:11,000
<b>It's a societal affirmation that the</b>

277
01:10:11,000 --> 01:10:12,800
<b>written word now holds the</b>

278
01:10:12,800 --> 01:10:14,033
<b>ultimate legal authority.</b>

279
01:10:14,833 --> 01:10:16,066
<b>The written document had</b>

280
01:10:16,066 --> 01:10:18,166
<b>become essential for ordinary life.</b>

281
01:10:19,066 --> 01:10:20,666
<b>So let's be clear about what</b>

282
01:10:20,666 --> 01:10:22,266
<b>the evidence actually shows.</b>

283
01:10:23,466 --> 01:10:25,100
<b>1. Classical Rome</b>

284
01:10:25,100 --> 01:10:26,866
<b>wasn't universally literate.</b>

285
01:10:27,233 --> 01:10:29,333
<b>It was already a highly stratified system</b>

286
01:10:29,333 --> 01:10:32,133
<b>where writing served elite functions and</b>

287
01:10:32,133 --> 01:10:33,966
<b>most knowledge was shared orally.</b>

288
01:10:34,399 --> 01:10:36,466
<b>2. Successor kingdoms maintained</b>

289
01:10:36,466 --> 01:10:37,933
<b>sophisticated legal and</b>

290
01:10:37,933 --> 01:10:39,333
<b>administrative systems.</b>

291
01:10:39,633 --> 01:10:42,366
<b>They kept taxes, wrote complex laws and</b>

292
01:10:42,366 --> 01:10:43,500
<b>continued Roman governance.</b>

293
01:10:44,433 --> 01:10:46,600
<b>3. The Carolingians launched a</b>

294
01:10:46,600 --> 01:10:47,666
<b>deliberate, centrally</b>

295
01:10:47,666 --> 01:10:49,733
<b>driven cultural revolution.</b>

296
01:10:50,199 --> 01:10:52,733
<b>They standardized script, produced</b>

297
01:10:52,733 --> 01:10:55,500
<b>massive legal codes, trained lay elites</b>

298
01:10:55,500 --> 01:10:57,533
<b>in Latin literacy and used</b>

299
01:10:57,533 --> 01:10:59,333
<b>writing to guarantee justice.</b>

300
01:10:59,933 --> 01:11:02,233
<b>Knowledge definitely became concentrated,</b>

301
01:11:02,766 --> 01:11:04,333
<b>centered around monasteries,</b>

302
01:11:04,633 --> 01:11:06,633
<b>cathedrals and royal courts.</b>

303
01:11:07,033 --> 01:11:08,866
<b>But it was developed strategically to</b>

304
01:11:08,866 --> 01:11:11,166
<b>build new Christian states with</b>

305
01:11:11,166 --> 01:11:12,766
<b>sophisticated legal structures.</b>

306
01:11:13,266 --> 01:11:15,833
<b>The term "dark ages" fundamentally fails</b>

307
01:11:15,833 --> 01:11:17,199
<b>to capture that reality.</b>

308
01:11:17,699 --> 01:11:19,633
<b>So why does it persist?</b>

309
01:11:20,233 --> 01:11:21,800
<b>Here's a provocative thought.</b>

310
01:11:22,166 --> 01:11:24,466
<b>The perceived darkness might just be the</b>

311
01:11:24,466 --> 01:11:26,733
<b>shadow cast by the success of the</b>

312
01:11:26,733 --> 01:11:27,933
<b>surviving written record.</b>

313
01:11:28,199 --> 01:11:30,233
<b>The Carolingian project successfully</b>

314
01:11:30,233 --> 01:11:32,666
<b>imposed a singular model across Europe.</b>

315
01:11:33,533 --> 01:11:36,266
<b>A Latin Christian learning model based on</b>

316
01:11:36,266 --> 01:11:38,166
<b>the written word as used by the elite.</b>

317
01:11:38,633 --> 01:11:40,899
<b>If that model was so successful, doesn't</b>

318
01:11:40,899 --> 01:11:44,199
<b>the term "dark ages" perhaps persist not</b>

319
01:11:44,199 --> 01:11:45,033
<b>because the period</b>

320
01:11:45,033 --> 01:11:46,399
<b>actually lacked knowledge?</b>

321
01:11:46,866 --> 01:11:48,533
<b>But because that successful agenda</b>

322
01:11:48,533 --> 01:11:49,899
<b>actively marginalized</b>

323
01:11:49,899 --> 01:11:51,233
<b>other kinds of knowledge.</b>

324
01:11:51,966 --> 01:11:54,199
<b>Vernacular cultures, pagan knowledge,</b>

325
01:11:54,633 --> 01:11:56,800
<b>local intellectual traditions, anything</b>

326
01:11:56,800 --> 01:11:58,199
<b>that didn't conform to</b>

327
01:11:58,199 --> 01:12:00,066
<b>Latin Christian elite standards.</b>

328
01:12:00,333 --> 01:12:02,033
<b>The perceived darkness might be what we</b>

329
01:12:02,033 --> 01:12:04,199
<b>lost because it didn't fit the agenda of</b>

330
01:12:04,199 --> 01:12:05,399
<b>the people holding the pen.</b>

331
01:12:06,100 --> 01:12:07,933
<b>And that forces us to look beyond what</b>

332
01:12:07,933 --> 01:12:09,533
<b>was written and ask who</b>

333
01:12:09,533 --> 01:12:10,666
<b>wasn't allowed to write.</b>

334
01:12:11,300 --> 01:12:13,066
<b>If this changed how you think about the</b>

335
01:12:13,066 --> 01:12:15,366
<b>middle ages, please subscribe.</b>

336
01:12:15,866 --> 01:12:17,333
<b>There's more Mid-Best in coming.</b>

